Q13 : what is java exception propagation? 
Ans : Java exception propagation refers to how an exception is passed up through the method call stack. 
      If a method doesn't handle an exception (no try-catch block is used), the exception is passed 
	  (propagated) to the caller method. This continues until it is caught, or if it isn't caught at all, 
	  the program terminates.
      example code  : 
            class A{  
			  void m(){  
				int data=50/0;  
			  }  
			  void n(){  
				m();  
			  }  
			  void p(){  
			   try{  
				n();  
			   }catch(Exception e){
			   System.out.println("exception handled");
			   }  
			  }  
			  public static void main(String args[]){  
			   A a1 = new A();
               a1.p();			   
			   System.out.println("normal flow...");  
			  }  
			}  	  
				   
        output - exception handled
		         normal flow...

