@ControllerAdvice - Global error handler
@ExceptionHandler - Handle specific exceptions

import org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ControllerAdvice;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ExceptionHandler;

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class) // Catch-all for any exception
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleGenericException(Exception ex) {
        return new ResponseEntity<>("Something went wrong: " + ex.getMessage(), HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
    }

    @ExceptionHandler(IllegalArgumentException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleIllegalArgument(IllegalArgumentException ex) {
        return new ResponseEntity<>("Invalid input: " + ex.getMessage(), HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST);
    }
	
	//here we can write the custome exception which is made by us but for that we need to make seperate class 
	@ExceptionHandler(ProductNotFoundException.class)
	public ResponseEntity<String> handleProductNotFound(ProductNotFoundException ex) {
	     
		return new ResponseEntity<>(ex.getMessage(), HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND);
	}

}

   //for 3rd exception ProductNotFoundException we need to create a seperate class which extends RuntimeException 
   public class ProductNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public ProductNotFoundException(String message) {
        super(message);//It goes to the parent class constructor and parent class here is RuntimeException class and this   RuntimeException class is already having the constructor 
        //“super(message)” calls the parent exception class (RuntimeException) constructor and stores the error message inside it. Later we can retrieve it using getMessage() in our global exception handler.”
    }
   }
   
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

@Service
public class ProductService {

    // Simulated in-memory data
    private static final Map<Long, Product> fakeProductDB = new HashMap<>();

    static {
        fakeProductDB.put(1L, new Product(1L, "Laptop"));
        fakeProductDB.put(2L, new Product(2L, "Mobile"));
        fakeProductDB.put(3L, new Product(3L, "Tablet"));
    }

    public Product getProductById(Long id) {
        Product product = fakeProductDB.get(id);
        if (product == null) {
            throw new ProductNotFoundException("Product with ID " + id + " not found.");
        }
        return product;
    }
}


   so at the end what happens is controller - > service -> if product not found it will go to the 
   GlobalExceptionHandler class and handle the ProductNotFoundException

   
   So in the flow:
   Controller ➝ Service ➝ (Product not found)
   we throw a ProductNotFoundException, which is then handled by the GlobalExceptionHandler class using the 
   @ExceptionHandler method.
   
   by handling exceptions with @ControllerAdvice and @ExceptionHandler, the exception will be shown as an HTTP
   response in Postman, not as a full stack trace in the console (unless you explicitly log it).
   
Q : @ControllerAdvice vs @RestControllerAdvice

ans : 
Annotation           |What It Does                                                |Output Format                                          
-------------------- |------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------ 
@ControllerAdvice    |Global exception handler for **web apps or MVC controllers**|Returns **HTML or views** (like error page) by default 
@RestControllerAdvice|Global exception handler for **REST APIs**                  |Returns **JSON** automatically (in postman)                        |
   
   
@RestControllerAdvice is a combination of:

@ControllerAdvice  (for global exception handling)

@ResponseBody (to return data in response body, like JSON or plain text)